actions.comment:
Thanks for the detailed report and SVG samples.

The SVG canvas writes the closing `</svg>` tag when the canvas is **disposed** — this is when Skia's internal `SkSVGCanvas` destructor finalizes the document. In your code, `using var` declarations defer disposal to the end of the enclosing scope, so `managedStream.ToArray()` runs before the canvas is destroyed.

Here's a workaround — use a scoped `using` block so the canvas is disposed before you read the stream:

```csharp
using var managedStream = new MemoryStream();
using (var canvas = SKSvgCanvas.Create(bounds, managedStream))
{
    using var theme = BuildTheme(ExportFormat.SVG);
    using var skiaRenderer = await CreateSkiaRenderer(theme, file, CanvasSize, CanvasSize) as SkiaRenderer;
    if (skiaRenderer == null) throw new ArgumentException("Renderer was null for SVG export");
    canvas.DrawMeasurement(skiaRenderer, filename, file, CanvasSize, CanvasSize);
}
// Canvas is disposed here — SVG document is now complete
result.Data = managedStream.ToArray();
```

Note: you can pass the `MemoryStream` directly to `SKSvgCanvas.Create` — the `Stream` overload handles the wrapping internally, so the explicit `SKManagedWStream` isn't needed.

This is the same pattern used in our [test suite](https://github.com/mono/SkiaSharp/blob/main/tests/Tests/SkiaSharp/SKCanvasTest.cs#L429-L441). The reason `SKFileWStream` appeared to work is likely that you read the file after all `using` blocks completed.
